Another important institution at Rome was the Moming Leve'e. The vestibule of the wealthy Roman's house might be seen crowded at an early hour by a multitude of visitors of all , classes: clients of the family, who received a daily allowance

Soon after the bath came a third great institution, the Dinner: for the Romans took but a mouthful of breakfast, followed bya lunch almost as slender, and reserved themselves for the final and principal meal‚ the ordinary time for which was about three o'elock in the asternoon, when the business of the day was over, It would exceed the limits of these remarks to describe the elaborate machinery and the multifarious and costly dishes that went to make up a Roman banquet.
